Begin by opening the command prompt. Type "del" followed by a space and the name of the file you want to delete. Press Enter. This will permanently delete the file. To permanently delete multiple files, separate them with a space. For example, "del file1.txt file2.txt" will delete both "file1.txt" and "file2.txt" from the hard drive. 

Step 2: Create a batch script. Open Notepad and type the commands necessary to delete multiple files. For example:

@echo off
for %%f in (*.txt) do (
    del "%%f"
)

This script will delete all text files in the current directory with the ".txt" extension.

Step 3: Save the batch script. Save it with a .bat file extension.

Step 4: Double-click the batch script to run it. A command prompt window will appear, asking if you want to permanently delete the files. Click "Y" to confirm. The files will be deleted permanently from the hard drive.
